===Etymology 2=== [[File:Marcus_Thames_Tigers_2007.jpg|thumb|A player swinging a baseball '''bat''' ({{senseno|en|club}})]]
From {{inh|en|enm|bat}}, {{m|enm|batte}}, from {{inh|en|ang|batt||bat, club, cudgel}}, probably of {{der|en|cel}} origin, compare {{cog|obt|bath||club, cudgel}} and modern {{cog|br|bazh||swagger stick}}, ultimately from a derivative of {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰedʰh₂-||to strike, beat, pierce}}, similar to the Gaulish source of {{cog|la|battuo||I beat, pound}}.<ref>Beekes, R. S. P. (1997). Sound Law and Analogy: Papers in Honor of Robert S.P. Beekes on the Occasion of His 60th Birthday. Netherlands: Rodopi, p. 312</ref>
====Noun==== {{en-noun}}
# A [[club]], made of wood like a [[baseball]] bat or otherwise, used as a [[weapon]] # {{senseid|en|club}} A [[club]] made of wood or aluminium used for striking the ball in sports such as [[baseball]], [[softball]] and [[cricket]]. # A [[turn]] at [[hitting]] the [[ball]] with a bat in a [[game]]. #: {{ux|en|You've been in for ages. Can I have a '''bat''' now?}} # A player rated according to skill in batting. #: {{ux|en|He's a good fielder and a valuable '''bat'''.}} # {{lb|en|two-up}} The piece of wood on which the [[spinner]] places the coins and then uses for throwing them.<ref>Sidney J. Baker, ''The Australian Language'', second edition, 1966, chapter XI section 3, page 242</ref> #: {{syn|en|kip|kylie|lannet|stick}} # {{lb|en|mining}} [[shale|Shale]] or [[bituminous]] shale. #* {{quote-text|en|year=1799|author=w:Richard Kirwan|title=Geological Essays |passage=bituminous shale ; which miners , if I mistake not , call '''bat'''}} # A [[sheet]] of [[cotton]] used for filling [[quilt]]s or [[comfortable]]s; [[batting]]. # A part of a [[brick]] with one whole end. <!--see brickbat--> # A [[stroke]]; a [[sharp]] [[blow]]. # {{lb|en|UK|Scotland|dialect}} A stroke of work. # {{lb|en|informal}} Rate of motion; speed. #* {{quote-text|en|year=1842|title=Sporting Magazine|page=251 |passage=On starting, The Nun led at a very slow pace for a quarter of a mile, when the Shrigley colt made running at a good '''bat'''.}} #* {{quote-text|en|year=1898|author=unknown author|title=Pall Mall Magazine |passage=a vast host of fowl {{...}} making at full '''bat''' for the North Sea.}} # {{lb|en|US|slang|dated}} A [[spree]]; a [[jollification]]; a [[binge]], [[jag]]. # {{lb|en|UK|Scotland|dialect}} Manner; rate; condition; state of health. # {{lb|en|Kent|Sussex}} A rough walking stick.<ref>A Dictionary of the Sussex Dialect. W.D. Parrish</ref><ref>A Dictionary of the Kentish Dialect and Provincialisms. W. D. Parish and W.F. Shaw</ref> #* {{RQ:Shakespeare Sonnets|poem=A Lover's Complaint|sig=K2|verso=1|page=190|passage=So ſlides he dovvne vppon his [[grained|greyned]] '''bat'''; / And comely diſtant ſits he by her ſide, {{...}}}}
