===Etymology 3=== {{etymid|en|to hit}} From {{inh|en|enm|baten|batten}}, {{m|enm|baten|t=to beat|id=to beat}}, from {{der|en|fro|batre||to beat}}, from {{der|en|LL.|batto|battere}}, from {{der|en|la|battuo|battuere}}, of {{unc|en|title=uncertain}} origin; perhaps of {{der|en|gem|-}} or {{der|en|cel|-}} origin. In modern English reinterpreted as a verbal derivative of Etymology 2. Compare {{m|en|batter}}, {{m|en|battery}}.
====Verb==== {{en-verb}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To hit with a bat or (figuratively) as if with a bat. #: {{ux|en|He '''batted''' the ball away with a satisfying thwack.}} #: {{ux|en|We '''batted''' a few ideas around.}} # {{senseid|en|take a turn at hitting}}{{lb|en|intransitive}} To take a turn at hitting a ball with a bat in sports like [[cricket]], [[baseball]] and [[softball]], as opposed to [[field]]ing. # {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[strike]] or [[swipe]] as though with a bat. #: {{ux|en|The cat '''batted''' at the toy.}} # {{lb|en|UK|dialect|obsolete}} To [[bate]] or flutter, as a [[hawk]].
